## 4.List and explain the main differences between site-to-site VPN and remote access VPN based on your Packet Tracer configurations, including at least two advantages and disadvantages of each approach.
=>Site-to-site VPN — advantages:

Always-on connectivity: once configured, all traffic between the offices flows automatically without any user action. Employees at Branch B can reach Branch A's file server like a local resource, every time.
Centrally managed: network admins control the entire tunnel from the routers. No software to install or manage on individual PCs.

Site-to-site VPN — disadvantages:

Inflexible: if a new office opens, a new tunnel must be configured on both routers. In large organizations with many branches, managing dozens of tunnels becomes complex.
Not suited for mobile workers: an employee working from home or a café cannot join the site-to-site tunnel — only devices physically at a branch are covered.

Remote access VPN — advantages:

Flexibility for mobile users: any employee anywhere in the world can securely connect to the office network from a laptop or phone, enabling hybrid and remote work.
User-level control: access can be granted or revoked per user (e.g., disable vpnuser account) without touching router configurations.

Remote access VPN — disadvantages:

Dependent on client software: each device needs a VPN client configured correctly. Updates, compatibility, and user errors introduce support overhead.
Performance varies: since each user's home internet is different, tunnel speed and latency are inconsistent — unlike a dedicated site-to-site leased line.


## 5.Document and submit the step-by-step configuration commands you used to set up the site-to-site VPN in Packet Tracer, including interface, tunnel, and routing commands.
=>Router-AStep 1 — LAN interface (Fa0/0)
! Configure LAN-facing interfaceRouter-A# configure terminalRouter-A(config)# interface FastEthernet0/0Router-A(config-if)# ip address 192.168.1.1 255.255.255.0Router-A(config-if)# no shutdownRouter-A(config-if)# exit
Router-AStep 2 — WAN interface (Fa0/1, public-facing)
! Configure WAN-facing interface (the tunnel source)Router-A(config)# interface FastEthernet0/1Router-A(config-if)# ip address 10.0.0.1 255.255.255.252Router-A(config-if)# no shutdownRouter-A(config-if)# exit
Router-AStep 3 — GRE tunnel interface (Tunnel0)
! Create GRE tunnel — source = own WAN IP, dest = remote WAN IPRouter-A(config)# interface Tunnel0Router-A(config-if)# ip address 172.16.0.1 255.255.255.252Router-A(config-if)# tunnel source FastEthernet0/1Router-A(config-if)# tunnel destination 10.0.0.2Router-A(config-if)# no shutdownRouter-A(config-if)# exit
Router-AStep 4 — Static route to Branch B via tunnel
! Route Branch B's LAN through the tunnel endpointRouter-A(config)# ip route 192.168.2.0 255.255.255.0 172.16.0.2Router-A(config)# endRouter-A# write memory
